@incollection{Bouchard2014,
abstract = {The recent advances in sensors network, engineering and ambient intelligence have brought us towards the dream of creating smart homes that can help humans in their everyday life. Many agree that the current technologies are sufficient to achieve this vision, but that major breakthroughs are needed on the software side (activity recognition, security, context awareness, oppor-tunistic network, etc.). In fact, it is the key component for enabling sensors and effectors to provide valuable services. Consequently, it is important for researchers to prototype and experiment on new algorithms and models in realistic setting (e.g. smart home). In order to face this challenge, many research teams have to build new experimental infrastructures without any background experience, guidance or even a real idea of their research needs and issues. Our team is composed of specialists in AI for cognitive assis-tance and has worked with four major smart home infrastructures. From that experience, we propose, in this chapter, a set of guidelines for design-ing and implementing an efficient smart home architecture on both hard-ware and software perspective. While it focuses on the particular context of cognitive assistance, this chapter provides insightful information about con-struction choice of smart homes in general. This chapter aims to be a step toward the development of algorithms (rapid prototyping) and smart homes research. Moreover, we share our recent experience with the construction of a new smart home and clinical trials conducted at our laboratory with real Alzheimer's subjects.},
